explanation:
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - The macro/inline used to obtain 'impl' may perform checks or side-effects (bounds checking, logging, lookups). Need its definition to know whether its execution is observable and whether removal would change behavior.

OS_impl_queue_table - The object/table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its layout/content determines whether impl can be NULL/invalid and whether the lookup has observable effects.

OS_impl_queue_internal_record_t - The type of 'impl' and the layout (field 'id' type and semantics). Required to know whether reading impl->id is safe/observable and whether accessing it has side-effects.

OS_object_token_t - The token type passed in; needed to determine how OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET/OS_ObjectIndexFromToken interprets it and whether usage here produces observable behavior.

OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - Shown in the static call graph as a callee of the macro expansion. Its behavior (validation, side-effects, error handling) affects whether the lookup is observable or removable.

mq_close - The POSIX/system call being invoked. Its semantics (closing a message queue descriptor, affecting system state) are central to deciding if the mq_close call is a dead operation — removing it likely changes system behavior if it has side-effects.

env errno - The global errno value used in the error branch; required to know whether reading it (and consequently logging it) is observable.

strerror - Used to produce the textual errno message for OS_DEBUG. Needed to determine whether the call has observable side-effects (e.g., uses static buffers) and thus whether the logging sequence could be considered dead.

OS_DEBUG - The logging macro/function invoked on error. Logging is an observable effect (I/O/timing); its definition determines whether the debug call is side-effect-free or not and whether removing it would alter program behavior.

OS_ERROR / OS_SUCCESS - The return-code constants assigned to return_code. Required to know whether their values/usage affect observable behavior of callers; removing assignments could change return semantics.

Rationale: To decide if any executed operation in OS_QueueDelete_Impl is dead code, the analyzer must know which calls/reads/writes produce observable effects (system state changes, I/O, timing). The above symbols cover the lookup mechanism, the record and token types, the system call invoked, the logging path and errno/string conversion, and the return values — all of which are needed to determine if removing any of these operations would not affect program behaviour.
